<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-01-07T16:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-01-07T16:45:00-05:00" n="935" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d935">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.1051/346: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Beaulac</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-01-07T16:00:00-05:45">January 7, 1930—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 7:11 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>3. Department’s instruction number 614, of December 27, 1929, second
                            paragraph. Do I understand correctly that the Department does not
                            consider banditry a military offense?</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Beaulac</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>